post_text:
West County Elementary will be offering a Back to Basics Program for all elementary students prior to the beginning of school. The Back to Basics Program is a summer program designed to provide students an opportunity to review and practice reading and math skills prior to the beginning of the school year.

This two-week program will be held Monday-Friday, 8:00 am - 3:00 pm, August 3rd - 14th.
Students MUST be enrolled in West County Elementary to participate in the Back to Basics Program.

All enrollment forms are due by July 24th.
Information regarding the program will be emailed to parents on or before July 30th

You must complete a registration form for EACH student enrolling.

post_text:
RETIREMENT SPOTLIGHT: MS. LILA BARNETT

How long have you been a teacher?
Ive taught for 30 years. All of my years have been at West County aside from one year at Richwoods.

What subjects have you taught?
I have taught elementary 3-5 grades and all core subjects at the high school level.

Whats your favorite memory of your teaching career?
My best memories are when a former student at West County takes the time to tell me what an impact I made in their life. I have had students tell me that they would not have graduated without me, chose to become a teacher because of me and named their child after me. My students are my school children!

What will you miss the most about teaching?
I will miss the students and my co-workers the most. I have two sons and grandchildren that attend West County so I will be around from time to time.

How do you plan on spending your retirement?
I plan on traveling some and being a grandparent.

CONGRATULATIONS, MS. BARNETT! ENJOY YOUR RETIREMENT! WE WILL MISS YOU!

Our sophomores were given the opportunity to participate in many leadership opportunities this spring/summer. Those interested had to submit an essay on the topic of leadership, which was scored and evaluated by a team of educators. The students that scored the highest were given the opportunity to attend a leadership opportunity. Although most of the conferences have been cancelled due to COVID-19, we still want to recognize our students that were selected to represent our school at these prestigious events:

HOBY Leadership Conference - Kylee Medlin & Allie Rawson
Missouri Leadership Seminar - Macey Bone
Rotary Youth Leadership Academy - Kaley Burr
Sophomore Pilgrimage - Sydney Cash

Congratulations, students! We are proud of you!

Attention all PK-12th grade students!

Did you know this week is Teacher Appreciation Week? Let's show our teachers how much we truly appreciate them all while showing off our creative abilities. We will do this in two fun ways!

1. Chalk Art Appreciation- Create your own chalk art showing your gratitude towards your favorite teachers. Email your pictures to byount@wcr4.org and they will be posted on the FB page for all your teachers to see!

2. Kindness Rock Project- find a rock and paint it expressing your appreciation for your teachers. Place the rock in front of the building of your choice or give rocks to buses when they deliver food.

post_text:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Mr. Korbyn Miller

Parent/Guardian Names: Jake & Deanna Miller

What are your plans after graduation?
My plans are to go to college at Missouri S & T.

What is your favorite High School memory?
My favorite memory is going to state for cross country.

What do you miss the most about school during the pandemic school closure?
I miss seeing my friends the most.

What is an accomplishment you are proud of?
I am proud of making it to state for cross country.

Whom do you admire, and why?
I don't admire anyone, because I think you should be your own person and plan to be different than other people.

Where do you see yourself in 10 years?
I see myself having a small family and a job in ten years.

What is your advice to underclassmen?
My advice to underclassmen is to not procrastinate on homework, it just makes it harder and more stressful than it needs to be.

Congratulations, Korbyn! We are so proud of you!

The plan is to begin in Irondale, then on to Leadwood and finish in Terre Du Lac.

Congratulations to all Preschool graduates! We are proud of you!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Mr. Tanner Thompson

Parent/Guardian Names: Amanda & Brent Thompson

What are your plans after graduation?
I plan to go to Mineral Area College to get a degree in business.

What is your favorite High School memory?
My favorite memory is hanging out with friends on incentive day.

What do you miss the most about school during the pandemic school closure?
I miss my friends.

What is an accomplishment you are proud of?
I am proud to be graduating and proud of getting through art class.

Whom do you admire, and why?
I admire Youtuber Markiplier. He successfully created his businesses.

Where do you see yourself in 10 years?
In ten years, I see myself working for and growing our family business.

What is your advice to underclassmen?
My advice to underclassmen is to hang on to every minute of high school. It goes by fast.

Congratulations, Tanner! We are so proud of you!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Miss Brittany Beckett

Parent/Guardian Names: Shannon & Randy Beckett

What are your plans after graduation?
Going to college to start a radiology program. (not sure which college yet).

What is your favorite High School memory?
All of them. Never thought Id miss school but I do.

What do you miss the most about school during the pandemic school closure?
Not being social with people.

What is an accomplishment you are proud of?
Making it this far, and overcoming anything in my way!

Whom do you admire, and why?
I admire Mrs. Black because shes always kind of been like a mother to everyone, and definitely knows how to make me laugh on my worst days.
I also admire Mr. Lashley, because I feel like I could talk to him about any troubles I had or ask for any advice and hed always know the answer.

Where do you see yourself in 10 years?
Having a job in radiology and having fun doing it.

What is your advice to underclassmen?
Enjoy it while you can.

Congratulations, Brittany! We are so proud of you!

post_text: Starting tonight, every Friday night, we will be joining schools around the country, and turning on our softball & baseball field lights. Lights will go on at 8:20pm which is 20:20 military time, and leaving them lit for 20 minutes and 20 seconds to honor our seniors of 2020. As most of you have heard, spring sports have been cancelled. This is just one of the few ways we plan to honor our seniors.
text: Starting tonight, every Friday night, we will be joining schools around the country, and turning on our softball & baseball field lights. Lights will go on at 8:20pm which is 20:20 military time, and leaving them lit for 20 minutes and 20 seconds to honor our seniors of 2020. shared_text:
Cj Wright
April 10 at 6:32 AM 路

My message to our girls was to stay positive through this and good things will happen, well as most of you know Missouri cancelled spring sports yesterday. For a few hours my positivity ran out, then I get this video message from one of my assistant coaches. It definitely brought a smile to my face and gave my household back some positivity. The smiles on every girls face brought a joy to us. I have been missing those moments when the success brings shear joy to the face of an athlete. I got a little of that watching this video. Needless to say Ive watched it over and over!! Thanks Hannah Marie Hollock, you did a fantastic job on this!! I hope everyone enjoys watching the 2020 WC Bulldogs softball team!!

Participating in the Caleb Carson Carlyon Invitational Tournament.

Getting books from the library.

I don't know.

Teaching in a high school.

Don't be a moron (like me).

post_text:
SENIOR PRODUCT PICKUP INFO:

Good Morning everyone!!

Just wanted to let you know that on Tuesday, April 28 from 10 am to 1 pm we will be passing out Cap, Gown and Senior Products from Jostens.
We will be in the front parking lot at the HS (by office) for you to Drive thru and pick up your products!! If you owe a balance to Jostens, this will need to be paid to us on that day!!! Payment must be in CASH ONLY. We will not have change, so you will need to bring the exact amount you owe!!! If you need to pay by credit or debit card, you will need to contact Jostens before April 28 to make your payment!! Their office number is Ironton is 573-546-7366.

If you can't make it on that day, we will keep your products at school and make arrangements for you to pick them up at a different time or you can pick them up when we go back on May 1.

I will be sending out a separate email to let you know your balance, if you owe a balance.

Hope everything is going well with you guys!! We miss you all terribly. Email me at smasters@wcr4.org if you have any questions!! See you soon!!

Mrs. Susan

We were sad to see our students leave today. We appreciate our parents & community working with us while we get some new systems in place.

Our Meals Service will start deliveries tomorrow. If you would like to sign-up for the Meals Service, go to this link - https://forms.gle/NR6a5ispyz2T8Tnv7

Our Remote Learning Resource Website is up & running. Our teachers have been working very hard uploading content, and will continue doing so throughout the closure. If you or your student has an issue using the Website, please email your childs teacher and we will look into the problem. The Website link is - https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1EDuHSeAfi0RZglKWl8FWaBFRODmeAjMd?usp=sharing

Also, if you have limited or no internet access, contact the Central Office at (573) 562-7535 x4 and we will get you some printed school-work packets.

We will have plenty of updates throughout this closure as we receive new information. All pertinent updates will be posted via social media, text, email, and the District website.

We look forward to seeing our students back in our schools!

post_text:
Jacob Hedgcorth 2 Dribble Scholarship

This scholarship is sponsored by Jacob Hedgcorth, owner of 2 Dribble Basketball, and is awarded to a West County Senior attending a college or technical school. Student must have maintained a minimum of B average throughout high school.

The scholarship recipient selected by scholarship committee will receive a one time $1000 to be used toward recipient's tuition and/or books. Award will be paid directly to the institution of the student's choice.

Scholarship applications are available in the West County High School Counseling Center. All applications must be returned to the Counseling Center no later than April 15th.

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS to the thirty three band and choir students who participated in district music contest on Saturday!!! Your performances were all amazing!!! Fourteen of these students received an Exemplary rating which qualifies them to go on and compete at state music contest in May. The following ensembles will be headed to state: The clarinet trio of Kaley Burr, Mykiah Perkins and Layni Barnes and the double mixed quartet of : Alivia Simily, Shayla Gidden, Kylee Medlin, Katelyn Herrera, Ethan Bryan, Quinten Flint, Josh Bice and Levi Johnson. The following solos will also be moving on to state: The vocal solos of Josh Neeley and Sydney Cash, the saxophone solo of Kaylee Burr and the bass solo of Sam AuBuchon. State Music Contest will take place on Saturday, May 2nd at MIZZOU. Good luck as you represent West County!!!!

post_text:
Parents of High School Students:

On Thursday, March 12th, we will be taking 50 high school students to the Technology Career Fair & Esports Expo at Central High School. On this field trip, students will learn about technology related careers and experience esports in action. Students with an interest in technology as a career are highly encouraged to attend.

In order to attend, students must:
*Have good attendance (at least 92%)
*Have no discipline
*Have no Ds or Fs

This expo is offered to students in grades 9-12, but older students will receive preference if we receive an overwhelming number of students sign-up to attend.

Don't miss out on their learning opportunity! If you would like for your child to attend, please have them complete the Google form in Mrs. Simily's Google Classroom, or see Mrs. Simily for details.

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLwB4XAZtgr5_b_ZdlhSoE1d9VgTvXv2PN

On Friday, February 21st, five local schools participated in the annual MAAA Swing Choir Festival. This event has taken place annually for over thirty years. It is held at a different MAAA school each year. This year the festival took place in the Performing Arts Center at Ste. Genevieve High School. Each school had 25 minutes to rehearse on stage and at 12:30 performed for an assembly of selected members from the Ste. Genevieve student body. PIctured are the students from the five area schools that participated: Bismarck, Central, Potosi, Ste. Genevieve and West County.

post_text:
Kathleen Juliette Education Award

This scholarship is awarded to a West County Senior by Roys Convenience Store & Twin Eagle in honor of Kathleen Juliette. Kathleen Juliette, Brad and Tyler Juliettes grandmother, was a Headstart Teacher in Cadet for 25 years. All applicants will be required to attach a typed essay of 500 words over the topic of The Importance of Education.

The scholarship recipient selected by scholarship committee will receive a one time $1000 ($500 donated by Roys Convenience Store & $500 donated by Twin Eagle) to be used toward recipients tuition and/or books. Award will be paid directly to the institution of the student's choice.

Return to the West County High School Counseling Center by April 1st.
